    "text": "## Opening\n\nI try to write about my work the way I think about it — plainly, and grounded in what I actually built or measured. I am Alex Rivera, applying to the MS in Artificial Intelligence at University of Georgia for Fall 2026. The program's concentration in Artificial Intelligence and its core-fit curriculum match where I want to spend the next two years. University of Georgia is where this work lives at the scale I need. I want two focused years to go from being an enthusiastic undergraduate researcher to someone who can own a non-trivial research project end to end.\n\n## Research background\n\nI completed my Bachelor of Science in Computer Science at University of Georgia. My cumulative GPA was 3.82 / 4.00.\n\nAs an undergraduate researcher in the UGA NLP Lab I led a retrieval-augmented code search project that asked a narrow question: does span-level supervision meaningfully improve retrieval on low-resource code repositories? I built the evaluation harness, designed an ablation... Led retrieval-augmented code search project end to end as an undergraduate researcher at the UGA NLP Lab. Designed an ablation over span granularity and built the evaluation harness.\n\nI built a multi-agent reinforcement learning environment that modeled a shared household pantry as a coordination game between independent restocking agents. The interesting part was not the reward function; it was the failure mode. Two agents with almost identical policies... Implemented a multi-agent RL environment in PettingZoo and PyTorch around a pantry-restocking coordination game. Diagnosed a free-rider failure mode and ran an ablation comparing no-communication baselines against a cheap communication channel.\n\n## Why this program\n\nThe MS in Artificial Intelligence is structured around the coursework and research I want to be inside of: strong:artificial intelligence, strong:machine learning, strong:deep learning, strong:computer vision. My own focus areas — natural language processing, multi-agent reinforcement learning, on-device inference — map directly onto that menu. I am specifically interested in working with Director of Graduate Studies, whose research in computer vision, machine learning overlaps with the problems I want to work on. Their published work in computer vision is part of what convinced me the fit was real.\n\n## Closing\n\nI am also applying to the Graduate Research Assistantship - NLP Lab, which (per its posting) supports this kind of work and is essential to my plan. I want the next two years to be focused and checkable, and I want advisors who make room for scope-limited experiments over broad, thin projects. I am applying for MS in Computer Science / Artificial Intelligence track and I am ready to contribute to the lab on day one.",
